    },
    {
      "id": "60a8fd3f70658b9bdf34cf2e0da6c7b95298e3ad",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-24 12:16:48.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 2.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "9dd480dac3f6ff12fe651f3d8e61736cee043930",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 179,
        "name": "Peng Tao",
        "email": "bergwolf@gmail.com",
        "username": "bergwolf"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-24 13:05:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nDo we care about non-ram pages at all? Looks like we just want to know the available ram size to determine Lustre's own cache/buffer sizes. Besides, num_physpages is not decreased in memory hotplug.\n\nTherefore IMHO, we should use totalram_pages rather than num_physpages in the first place. And totalram is available in all kernels. I can change the score if you convince me that num_physpages is better.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "eb007aee3809c7e4cd0aecc9727b724ceb26591e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 251,
        "name": "Bob Glossman",
        "email": "bob.glossman@intel.com",
        "username": "bogl",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-09-24 13:41:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nMaybe the snapshot of linux client code in the upstream 3.11 kernel source in fc19 is old, but I still see references to num_physpages there.  I agree that totalram_pages is probably a better choice.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "8353bd25e1e55816b87643fb1586853fa71e38a8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-24 13:48:13.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nOkay looked at the source code from 2.6.32 on and I do see that totalram_pages is there. I like this fact since we don't have to do any testing for versions. Also I see this variable looks to be properly handled in various memory management conditions (swap, hotplug) than num_physpages. I will update the patch soon.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
